The overall purpose of the project is to support the government's efforts in increasing access and improving the quality of girls' education through capacity building and targeted interventions at both institutional and community level.

Geographically, the project will target the most disenfranchised and hardest to reach areas of Pakistan where girls' access to primary education are most challenged and has high illiteracy rate of adults particularly among women.

As follow-up of the decision of the First Intergovernmental Conference on Angkor, held in Tokyo in 1993, the working procedures of the Committee were established. It was decided that the ICC-Angkor would be co-chaired by France and Japan in collaboration with the APSARA National Authority, UNESCO provides the services of standing secretariat. The financial mechanism established on the initiative of Japan and France also foresaw that the cost of the ICC-Angkor meetings should be borne by these two countries and UNESCO. Respectively, since 2009, 2019, the APSARA and Sambor Prei Kuk National Authorities have also financially contributed to the ICC meetings. The Site of Sambor Prei Kuk, inscribed on the World Heritage List, was officially included in the mechanism of ICC-Angkor in 2019.

The overall purpose of this workplan is ensure a proper evaluation coverage of the sector’s programme and projects, for accountability, learning and decision-making. The key activities are the delivery and dissemination of corporate evaluations on strategic/ global and thematic topics and an annual synthesis report of all UNESCO evaluations. It also involves support to the decentralized evaluation function by building the capacity of UNESCO staff through a dedicated training programme; financing and managing Regional Evaluation Associates in five duty stations (to start in 2025) and animating the Evaluation Focal Point Network and the UNESCO Evaluation Knowledge Hub.

This activity will contribute to the reduction of gender inequality and empower all women and girls in line with MONDIACULT declaration and the objectives of the Plan for the Recovery of Cultural Industries and the Arts to 2030 developed by the Ministry of Culture of Peru with the technical assistance of UNESCO. This activity will focus its efforts on building capacity in local governments in the development of cultural plans and other measures that contribute to the reduction of gender inequalities through culture.

The biennium workplan for engineering that involves institutional and human capacity building and advocacy in the field of engineering.

The basic and engineering sciences constitute the core of modern science, and they are, and will still be, at the root of any innovative science answer to meet basic human needs and solve pressing challenges of sustainable development. From quality engineering education at all academic levels, to building institutional capacity, to promoting and catalyzing international scientific collaboration and networks, to facilitating access to scientific information, in particular through open science and open access to scientific information, UNESCO’s work in capacity development is at the heart of its mandate in science. UNESCO will, therefore, continue to implement its capacity-building and awareness-raising mandate in engineering.

Objectives:
1)	Raise awareness of the important role of engineering for the SDGs and promote international dialogues and cooperation;
2)	Provide institutional and human capacity-building opportunities for Member States to enhance their capacities in addressing global challenges, as well as for youth and women engineers, with a focus on African countries;
3)	Continue to develop partnerships and conduct resource mobilization to build networks and invite more partners and stakeholders to contribute or benefit from the UNESCO engineering programme.

Key activities:

•	The Entrepreneurship Bootcamp series for early-career scientists and engineers bootcamps will be continued in this biennium with two specific bootcamps organised for African and Latin American early-career engineers, especially in support of young female engineers. At least 70 early-career engineers, 50% women, will be supported through these bootcamps. 

•	Through the partnerships developed with ISSET and Space Prize Foundation, a capacity-building activity for students and teachers will be implemented using Space as a vehicle to inspire and educate students about space science and STEM. At least 20 science teachers will be supported through this activity. 

•	Finalise an Agreement with the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) to produce the next Engineering report.  

•	The World Engineering Day for Sustainable Development will be celebrated in collaboration with the World Federation of Engineering Organizations (WFEO) through an event (seminar/webinar/Hackathon) to increase global awareness and understanding of the role of engineering in addressing the many challenges faced by humanity, such as mitigating the impact of climate change and advancing sustainable development.

•	The World Metrology Day will be celebrated with the support of Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (BIPM) through an event (seminar/webinar/exhibition) to increase global awareness and understanding of the role of metrology in modern life.

•	The Africa Engineering Week (AEW)will be supported and strengthened to inspire and educate the African youth, increase the visibility of the engineering world in Africa and showcase how engineers are the ultimate problem solvers and crucial players in addressing our continent’s most pressing challenges. During Africa Engineering Week, a bootcamp within the Entrepreneurship Bootcamp series will be organised, especially in support of young African female engineers. At least 35 early-career engineers in Africa, 50% women, will be supported through this bootcamp. 

•	Collaborations among Category 2 Centres (C2Cs) in Engineering will be encouraged through annual meetings to foster interregional collaboration and promote research and training hubs of excellence in engineering, with special emphasis on Africa and young female engineers. 

•	New partnerships will be discussed to help UNESCO implement its goals and achieve ambitious results and impact in the new biennium.

•	The International Decade of Sciences for Sustainable Development (IDSSD) has been proclaimed in August 2023. The decade will run from 2024-2033. All activities performed in this work plan will be under the umbrella of the IDSSD.
